I’m a writer so I am supposed to come up with words for any occasion but I am having a hard time expressing just how deep I am in my feelings watching my son graduate. He worked so hard to earn a spot at Stanford and pushed himself to new levels of excellence and perseverance through four years of college like no other — marked by Covid and upheaval and uncertainty. And through it all he found community, he found joy, he became confident in his unique vision and reveled in following his own path. He became a leader on campus. He won the James Lyon Award for service and he was chosen to deliver a special addesss to his fellow students at the Black Graduation Ceremony.  Pride is too small a word for what I feel. When Norris was a toddler he lost his hearing for a time due to ear infections and a doctor told me he might not ever learn how to speak. I knew that doctor was wrong and we found a new one. I knew that little boy with the bright eyes and the big heart — evident even then — would light up the world. I can’t wait to watch him soar in this next journey. So happy for you @thenorrisjay. So full of joy in your accomplishments. Beaming not just what what you’ve done but for who you’ve become.  #mamalove #familystrong

The cover of my upcoming book was released today with an original painting by @kadirnelson called Totem. The book is called “Our Hidden Conversations: What Americans Really Think About Race And Identity” and it’s based on my 14 years of work at @theracecardproject. The publisher is @simonandschuster and the release date is Jan 16th, 2024. Preorder now. Spread the word. I can’t wait to share this book with the world. Thanks to everyone who has made this journey possible.

This is a powerful collection of candid stories from hundreds of individuals that float like a river around the 13 essays written by me that are based on my work at @theracecardproject over the past 14 years.  Who knew that an invitation to share 6-word stories on race would open up a torrent of humanity, humor and heartbreak.  The book is called, “Our Hidden Conversations: What Americans Really Think about Race and Identity.” Kadir Nelson has done the beautiful cover art and the book is also filled with more than 250 photos that add a shimmering dimension to the stories people share. Published by @simonandschuster Released on 1/16/24.  Preorder now. 
Spread the word.

I just want to send up a whoosh of gratitude to Kadir Nelson for his vision, his talent, his careful eye, his steady hand and his great big heart.  I have been a fan of his work for more than two decades and to have one of his paintings grace the cover of my upcoming book is a dream come true. Forever grateful to you @kadirnelson

We are smiling like Christmas because we reached the finish line  on the book project. @gogliabear and I have been working together on @theracecardproject for fourteen years, brick by brick collecting stories and building a powerful archive around the lived experience of race and identity in America captured from all sides.  This book was one of the most challenging, complex, steep and yes, rewarding projects I have ever undertaken. Thankful I had a team that brought passion, good humor and true stamina (both physical and emotional) to this effort.  We hold a mirror up to America in our work and because the subject is race, you will not like everything you see. But, you will have a better understanding of the forces that confine and define us.  The grind continues, but todsy we take a moment for deep breaths, high fives, and maybe even a hip shake. Love ya MB

Just love hearing from folks who’ve been listening to my new @audible original podcast. The show always begins with a simple question - “Tell me about Your Mama’s Kitchen.” It’s about memory, legacy and identity. So far, we’ve had @MichelleObama and @GayleKing share delicious memories from their mamas’ kitchens — including the recipes and meals that evoke a sense of home. Soon, we’ll be sharing details and instructions for the beloved recipes my guests serve up on the show so you can make them in your own kitchen! Until then — stay tuned, and be sure to listen to new episodes of #yourmamaskitchen from @Audible every Wednesday. Next week we hear from @dnice and trust me, it’s delightful. While you’re here, tell me about the favorite dish from YOUR mama's kitchen in the comments!  Was it a holiday dish? A weekday staple? A killer desert or a dish that reached back to your family’s cultural roots? I’ll start.  My mom used to bake me a chocolate cake every year for my birthday and she would put a little coffee in the frosting to give it a kick. I still smile when I think about the thick slab of cake I ate at every birthday celebration. Thanks mom!

Ingredients:
2 parts Maker’s Mark Bourbon
3-4 fresh mint leaves
1 part fresh lemon juice
1/2 part simple syrup (1:1 ratio of sugar and water)
2 parts sparkling water
Ice cubes
Lemon wheel and a sprig of mint for garnish

We know that people have STRONG opinions about this dish.  Not all mac and cheese is created equal. Let’s start there. It’s a matter of taste, tradition, and let’s be honest… a matter of skill. A seasoned cook can throw together a batch of Mac & Cheese without looking at a recipe. They know just how much cheese to add. They know exactly how to make that cream sauce on the stove and the moment when to add to the noodles before tossing in all that cheese. They know exactly how long to bake it, and whether or not to put some sort of breadcrumb on top to sap up some of the oil and create a little crunch. They know how to get it just the right golden brown color. Anyone who can do all that has usually been making Mac & Cheese for years. Repetition brings mastery, flavor and texture. It’s a dish that is both satisfying and intimidating, especially if cooking for a crowd. 

Peggy, King‘s recipe is a good starting point for those just learning how to master Mac & Cheese and an interesting excursion for anyone who is looking to refine or perfect the recipe. @dnice ended our conversation on the #yourmamaskitchen podcast with a story about one of those home-cooked meals that elicited a range of emotions for him.. He returned home one day to an unusual odor coming from the kitchen. The odor he remembered from the kitchen that day was wafting all throughout the house and while his first reaction was akin to — What in the heck is THAT?!? He quickly settled into a place of gratitude because what he was smelling was an act of love —  the result of a mother cooking a big pot of southern style cabbage for her son.
 
So it is only fitting that we serve up a recipe for Southern Style Cabbage for this week’s episode.

Here’s what you will need 

1/4 pound bacon cooked crisp or one package of cubed pancetta cooked until crisp

2-3 tablespoons drippings from the bacon or pancetta

Two tbsp butter

One cup chicken broth. 

One medium size yellow onion coarsely chopped

Two large garlic cloves finely chopped

One medium head of green cabbage with leaves removed 

Pepper, Salt, Garlic Salt , Cayenne pepper ( I like the Louisiana Creole blend from the @thespicehouse ) 

Preparation

Chop the onions, garlic and cabbage ahead of time so you can move quickly once the droppings are heated in the skillet. 

Cut cabbage to create thick ribbons. 

Cook bacon so it has a nice crisp so you can easily crumble it later or prepare the pancetta so it has just the beginning of crunch. Heat some of the drippings from that bacon or pancetta in a deep skillet or dutch oven. 

Next add onions and cabbage to the drippings along with the two tbsps of butter and stir until onions start to become translucent and the cabbage starts to wilt. Add  chopped garlic. 

Add seasonings.

As everything stats to wilt add one cup chicken stock and one third of the bacon or pancetta and simmer on low for 25 minutes. 

Just before serving add the remaining chopped bacon or pancetta and a light sprinkle of salt and pepper. If you wanted to turn this into more of a main dish you could also add cooked sliced sausage 

Serves 4-6

Andy Garcia’s Cuban Chicken Fricassee (Serves 8-10)

INGREDIENTS: Chicken thighs, garlic, lime & orange juice, onions, peppers, tomato paste, salt, green peas, olive oil, raisins, green olives, capers, black pepper, Spanish dry sherry wine (or apple cider vinegar), potatoes.

PREPARATION: Marinade chicken overnight in orange juice, lime juice, onions, peppers and lots of garlic. Brown chicken and set aside. Sauté peppers and onions and garlic  with some of the marinade juice. Deglaze with sherry. Add remaining ingredients, cook till chicken is tender. Add potatoes in the last 30-45 mins.  Frozen instead of canned peas will lower sodium content. 

Serve with fried plantains and white rice. 

SIDE: Avocado and Onion salad with olive oil and balsamic dressing.

On the first day of Gumbo we talk about attitude. When you are new to making Gumbo, it’s easy to get intimidated and feel like you have to find a recipe that you can follow to the letter so you don’t mess things up.  There are some aspects of Gumbo were you do need to stick to fundamentals. The most important is The Roux to make sure that you get it to the right texture and color and most importantly that it doesn’t burn.  But Gumbo, like jazz should have a little bit of improvisation so that it matches your family’s flavor palette and the ingredients that are available were you happen to be.  My late Aunt Odiev ( oh how I loved her) long ago told me that the best cooks don’t keep their nose inside cookbooks. Yes, they use cookbooks and keep them handy, but they also use the powers of observation, and they let themselves feel the rhythms of the kitchen and the way certain flavors know how to dance together.  lt sounded like sorcery when I was younger but now I fully understand the important alchemy or skill, improvisation and attitude.

#12DaysOfGumbo  On day two it’s all about Roux — the place where gumbo begins and the most important step. Making a Roux is actually simple — as long as you are not in a rush.  It’s a combination of oil and flour, usually in equal amounts cooked slowly until it makes a thick consistency. Not like gravy. Not like slurry. It needs to be smooth, so make sure you are using your spoon to break down the lumps. I always use a wooden spoon. Gotta be a wooden spoon.  This takes time. Don’t rush it.  You want to let the Roux darken and this is where people have different standards. Some like it tan like leather. Others a bit darker like a Cooper penny. I tend to reach a bit deeper in color which means more time and more patience.

• Making a Roux requires focus.  It’s best not to be distracted by anything. Don’t answer the phone or keep one eye on the TV because once the color starts to deepen, things happen fast and you will need to move on to the next step of adding the onions. 

• Some people make their roux in a skillet and then transfer that to the Gumbo pot (you are going to be hearing tips and observations from members of the Gumbo Tribe throughout these 12 days who have different recipes and approaches to their Gumbo). In our family, we make our Roux in a heavy bottomed pot so the final product sops up allllllll the flavors. 

• A word about the oil.  Technically, you can use almost any oil that has a high smoke point — canola, vegetable, lard or peanut oil. Avoid olive oil. Burns too fast. As for my family. — we make our ROUX with bacon fat. I fry most of the bacon in a skillet and save the bacon fat. But— I also fry a few pieces of bacon in the heavy bottomed gumbo pots, remove the bacon and add more bacon grease leftover from the bacon I fried up in the skillet.  It’s very important not to let the Roux get scorched.  This is the risk-taking part of Roux. You want the color to darken but not so much that you get a scald.  That will step on that nutty flavor you are looking for.

For the 4th day of #12DaysOfGumbo, I’m passing the mic to my daughter @ajaisabel to share her gumbo story and to talk about two things that are just as important to the gumbo as the ingredients: the pot and the wooden spoon.

Let’s start with the spoon: technically, you can use and kind of spoon, or even a whisk. But to get the right consistency, I suggest a wooden spoon. It allows you to get in and scrape the pot without damaging it. You can pound out those little clumps of flour, and I occasionally tap the spoon against the side of the pan so the roux almost .. relaxes when it starts to thicken. 

Now, a word about the pot. Again, you can use almost any kind of pot - over the centuries, people have been making do with any pot they have. But if you can, get something with a heavy bottom that distributes heat evenly. You will have much better results for the low-and-slow method of cooking needed in order to make a classic gumbo. As my daughter, I tend to protect my gumbo pot .. I don’t want people making popcorn or anything else that might burn up the bottom or leave distinctive flavors behind that clash with the rich taste of the gumbo. 

The main thing I hope you take from the story my daughter shared is that gumbo - like anything stepped in tradition and cooked with love - is its own kind of medicine for body, soul, and mind. We need a world with fewer walls, #LongerTables, and more gumbo. ❤️

Day 5 of #12DaysOfGumbo is all about the meats! Now, some people prefer an all-seafood gumbo.  And that certainly is delicious! But as for me and our family recipe for Xmas Gumbo? Oh, we gon’ have some meat in there.. 

First: bacon. If you watched Day 3 of Gumbo, you know that my recipe starts with a healthy dose of bacon grease. (We promise to get in the gym to work it off)  Mix that with some flour,  and work slowly and carefully and you’ve got your Roux. 

Next up: after you add onions and celery and all those special spices, it’s time for chicken. Baked chicken, in particular. You may be tempted to skip a step and just put the chicken in there before pre baking.  And welll….to each their own. But I find that baking it first seasoned welll helps to bring out the flavor in the chicken and makes it easier for it to blend together with the other ingredients.  Also, the pan juices will add flava. 

And finally: some good andouille sausage.  Do we andouille?  You know we do baybee. Gotta get that New Orleans flavor up in there. Andouille sausage has a delicious kick to it that catches your attention, but isn’t quite spicy enough to where it overpowers the other ingredients  I sauté my saugage ahead of adding it to the Gumbo pot. 

As you can see Gumbo is not really a one pot meal.  The extra effort is worth it.  #worthethic
